Implement clime-app, clime-group, clime-command, clime-option, clime-arg macros that build the command tree declaratively. Macros expand into tree construction calls. clime-option FLAGS list declares both long and short aliases. Boolean flags inferred from :count t or :type boolean or nargs=0. :multiple t marks repeatable options. Groups with subcommands restrict positional args to fixed-count required only.
** Design
*** File: clime-dsl.el (new file)

Declarative macros that expand into clime-core constructor calls,
building a command tree. The DSL is the primary authoring interface.

*** Target usage example

,#+begin_src elisp
(clime-app myapp
  :version "1.0.0"
  :env-prefix "MYAPP"

  (clime-option verbose ("-v" "--verbose") :count t :help "Increase verbosity")
  (clime-option json ("--json") :nargs 0 :help "Output JSON")

  (clime-command show
    :aliases ("get")
    :help "Show a resource"
    (clime-arg id :help "Resource ID")
    (clime-option format ("-f" "--format") :default "text" :help "Output format")
    (clime-handler (ctx)
      (let ((id (clime-ctx-get ctx 'id)))
        (message "Showing %s" id))))

  (clime-group dep
    :help "Dependency management"

    (clime-command add
      :help "Add a dependency"
      (clime-arg id :help "Dependency ID")
      (clime-option blocking ("--blocking") :nargs 0 :help "Mark as blocking")
      (clime-handler (ctx)
        (message "Adding dep %s" (clime-ctx-get ctx 'id))))

    (clime-command remove
      :aliases ("rm")
      :help "Remove a dependency"
      (clime-arg id :help "Dependency ID")
      (clime-handler (ctx)
        (message "Removing dep %s" (clime-ctx-get ctx 'id))))))
,#+end_src

Result: `myapp` is bound to a `clime-app` struct ready for `clime-parse`.

*** Macro design

**** clime-app (name &rest body)
- NAME is an unquoted symbol, becomes the variable name AND the app name string
- BODY is a mix of keyword args and child forms
- Keyword args: :version, :env-prefix, :help, :json-mode
- Child forms: clime-option, clime-arg, clime-command, clime-group
- Expands to: (defvar NAME (clime-make-app ...)) with children wired up

**** clime-command (name &rest body)
- NAME: unquoted symbol → string name
- Keyword args: :help, :aliases, :hidden
- Child forms: clime-option, clime-arg, clime-handler
- clime-handler is (clime-handler (ctx) BODY...) → lambda

**** clime-group (name &rest body)
- Like clime-command but with child clime-command/clime-group forms
- Keyword args: :help, :aliases, :hidden
- Optional clime-handler for group invocation without subcommand

**** clime-option (name flags &rest plist)
- NAME: unquoted symbol
- FLAGS: literal list of strings (NOT quoted — macro quotes it)
- Rest is a plist: :type, :help, :required, :default, :nargs, :env,
  :count, :multiple, :group, :hidden

**** clime-arg (name &rest plist)
- NAME: unquoted symbol
- Rest is a plist: :type, :help, :required, :default, :nargs

**** clime-handler (args &rest body)
- Only valid inside clime-command or clime-group
- ARGS is a lambda-list (typically (ctx))
- Expands to a lambda

*** Implementation approach
- Each macro is a defmacro that returns a quoted form (constructor call)
- clime-app is the top-level; it walks its body, separating keywords from
  child forms, and generates the full tree in one expansion
- Actually simpler: make clime-option/clime-arg/clime-handler just return
  quoted data (not real macros), and have clime-app/clime-command/clime-group
  process them as DSL forms. This avoids evaluation order issues.
- So clime-option etc. are NOT standalone macros — they're recognized
  syntax inside clime-app/clime-command/clime-group body parsing.
- Implementation: a single recursive body-parser function that walks forms.

*** Key design choices
- clime-handler wraps body in a lambda at compile time — no runtime cost
- Names are symbols in source, converted to strings for the tree
- The variable binding (defvar) means the app is available at load time
- Parent refs are set by clime--set-parent-refs (already exists in parse.el)
