Deterministic single-pass parser implementing the scope parse loop from the design doc. Features: long options (--name value, --name=value), short options (-n value), short bundles (-abc for booleans), boolean flag inference (no value consumed), short-to-long alias resolution, :multiple option collection, positional arg validation with nargs enforcement, :rest/:nargs + for multi-value positionals, -- ends all option parsing, root global options resolved from any position before --. Group positional ambiguity policy enforced.
** Design
*** File: clime-parse.el (new file)

Separate module for the parser. clime-core.el has the data model,
clime-parse.el has the parse engine.

*** Public API

**** clime-parse (app argv) → clime-parse-result
Main entry point. Takes a clime-app and a list of string tokens (argv).
Returns a clime-parse-result struct on success, signals an error on failure.

**** clime-parse-result struct
- command — the resolved clime-command (leaf node)
- path — list of node names from root to command, e.g. ("myapp" "dep" "add")
- params — plist of (param-name . value) for all resolved params across all scopes
  Root options, group options, command options, and positional args all merged.
  Param names are symbols (matching the option/arg :name).
- rest — list of leftover tokens when a :rest arg consumed them

*** Parse algorithm (single pass)

State variables:
- current-node: starts at app root
- option-parsing: t (set to nil on --)
- root: the app (for global option fallback)
- params: accumulator plist
- arg-index: tracks which positional arg we're consuming in current node
- path: accumulator for node names

Loop over argv tokens:
1. If token is "--": set option-parsing to nil, continue
2. If option-parsing and token looks like an option (starts with -):
   a. Handle --name=value: split into flag + value
   b. Handle short bundles: -abc → expand to -a -b -c if all boolean
      If not all boolean, treat as -a with "bc" as potential value? No —
      treat -abc as single short flag -a consuming "bc"... Actually no.
      Rule: -abc is a bundle ONLY if -a, -b, -c are all boolean in scope.
      If -a is not boolean, treat -abc as -a with next token as value.
      If -a is boolean but -b is not, that's ambiguous — error.
      Simpler rule for MVP: -abc is a bundle attempt. Expand left-to-right.
      If any char is not a known boolean flag, error.
   c. Look up flag in current-node options → found? consume it
   d. Else look up flag in root options (global) → found? consume it
   e. Else error: unknown option "%s" for command "%s"
3. If current-node is a group and token matches a child name/alias
   AND required positional args for current group are satisfied:
   - Push current-node's name to path
   - Descend: current-node = child
   - Reset arg-index to 0
4. Else: treat as positional for current-node
   - If arg-index < len(args): consume into params under arg name
     - If arg has :nargs :rest: collect this and all remaining non-option tokens
   - Else: error "unexpected positional argument"

Consuming an option value:
- If option is boolean/count: no value consumed. Increment count or set t.
- If option is :multiple: append value to list in params
- Else: consume next token as value. Error if no next token.

After loop:
- Check all required args/options have values (across all scopes visited)
- Apply defaults for missing optional params
- Return clime-parse-result

*** Error signaling
Use a custom error symbol `clime-usage-error` so callers can distinguish
usage errors (exit 2) from runtime errors (exit 1).
(define-error 'clime-usage-error "CLI usage error")

*** Scope for this bead (what's NOT included)
- Stdin sentinel: parser treats "-" as a normal string value.
  The stdin bead (clime-ld5) will hook into value consumption.
- Type conversion: parser returns raw strings. Type conversion is a
  separate concern (post-parse or integrated later).
- Help/version interception: parser does NOT handle --help/--version.
  Those are handled by the dispatch layer (clime-rhz).
  Actually, reconsidering: --help should short-circuit parsing.
  For MVP, if --help or -h is encountered, signal a distinct condition
  `clime-help-requested` with the current node, so dispatch can handle it.
  Same for --version at root.
